    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-11-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-11-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="1106"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1106">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/10711.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to Costa Rica</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-11-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 28, 1913</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge receipt of the
                    Department’s cablegram of November 10, 2 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d1106fn1">See
                        footnote to the telegram of November 7, 10 p.m.</note> It was several days
                    before the Department’s instructions could be carried out, when I addressed the
                    following letter to the Foreign Office:</p>
                <p>(Quotes his note<note n="2" xml:id="d1106fn2">Not printed.</note> of November 15,
                    embodying the instruction above referred to.)</p>
                <p>Up to this time I have received no reply to the letter just quoted.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">E. J. Hale</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
